          "body": "Verses 4-5 are the psalm's most practically dense unit — five imperatives in two verses. 'Tremble and do not sin' (*ragaz* and *al techeta*): the agitation the adversaries feel (whether Davidic opponents feeling the weight of his rebuke, or David himself counseling his own soul) is permitted, but it must not cross into sinful response. The LXX reads *orgizesthe* (be angry) for *ragaz*, and this is the text Paul directly quotes in Ephesians 4:26 — 'Be angry, and do not sin: do not let the sun go down on your wrath.' The New Testament apostle reads verse 4 as universally applicable counsel. 'Meditate in your heart upon your bed' (*imru bilevavkem al mishkavchem*): the night hours are not wasted in rumination but redirected into heart-speech with God. 'Be still' (*damam*): stop the inner noise. The second *Selah* follows immediately — the command to *damam* is reinforced by the musical pause. 'Offer the sacrifices of righteousness' and 'trust in the Lord' (4:5) close the instruction: right worship and genuine trust are the twin postures that complete the response. The verb *batach* (trust) will reappear as the noun *betach* (security) in 4:8 — the psalm's own argument seals itself."
