        "excerpt": "But know that the Lord has set apart the godly man for Himself; the Lord hears when I call to Him.",
        "body": "Verse 2 addresses the 'sons of men' (*bene ish*) — men of prominence who have converted David's honor (*kavod*) into shame (*kelimmah*) by pursuing *riq* (emptiness) and *kazav* (deception/lies). The double 'how long?' (*ad mah*) is the lament formula of a person who has been waiting for justice and is beginning to register the length of the wait. It is not loss of faith; it is honest prayer under sustained attack. The ancient Near Eastern honor-shame culture made reputation (*kavod*) a social currency as real as money. David's opponents are not merely disagreeing with him; they are attacking his standing in the community.\n\nVerse 3 answers with a theological argument that cuts the honor-shame system at its root. 'The Lord has set apart the godly man for Himself' (*palah*). The verb *palah* means to make distinct, to distinguish miraculously — used of God's separating Israel from Egypt at the Exodus. The application to the individual *chasid* is radical: Yahweh's sovereign election of the covenant-loyal person is the final word on that person's standing. No human court of public opinion can overrule it. Peter Davids's observation about James 4:6 applies equally here: God's grace to the humble is His active opposition to what pride would build — the *chasid*'s standing is secured not by social competition but by divine distinction.\n\nThe *chasid* (faithful one, covenant-loyal one) is not a moral perfectionist but a person whose identity is located in *hesed* — the steadfast covenant love of God. This is why the second clause of verse 3 — 'the Lord hears when I call to Him' — is not a general prayer promise but the specific privilege of the *chasid*. The hearing God is the God of the covenant. The one whom Yahweh has set apart has access to Yahweh that the 'sons of men' chasing emptiness do not.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Palah* appears in Exodus 8:22; 9:4; 11:7 for God's distinguishing Israel from Egypt in the plagues. *Chasid* derives from *hesed* — the covenant-loyalty that is God's most comprehensive attribute toward His people. *Kavod* (honor/glory) and *kelimmah* (shame/reproach) are the two poles of the ancient honor culture that Yahweh's election transcends."
