        "body": "Verses 4-5 are the psalm's most practically demanding unit, and verse 4 carries unexpected canonical weight. The command *ragaz* ('tremble' or 'be agitated') names a real inner state — the Hebrew allows for righteous anger as well as anxious trembling. The LXX translates it *orgizesthe* ('be angry'), and this is precisely the text Paul quotes in Ephesians 4:26: 'Be angry, and do not sin; do not let the sun go down on your anger.' Paul's citation treats Psalm 4:4 as a universal command for the Christian community — the psalm's situation (a believer under false accusation, managing internal agitation) is paradigmatic for all believers who face provocation. The apostolic use confirms what the Hebrew syntax already suggests: agitation itself is not forbidden; the prohibition is against crossing from agitation into sinful response.\n\nThe command to 'meditate in your heart upon your bed' (*imru bilevavkem*) redirects the agitation. 'Meditate' here is literally 'speak' (*amar*) — speak to your heart, on your bed. This is the kind of inner dialogue Psalms 42-43 model ('Why are you in despair, O my soul?') and that the Puritan tradition developed as 'speaking to the soul.' The bed becomes not a place of anxious rumination but of intentional heart-conversation with truth. 'Be still' (*damam*) closes the instruction: silence the internal noise. The *Selah* that follows is the musical enactment of the command — a pause, a breath, a deliberate cessation.\n\nVerse 5's twin commands — 'offer the sacrifices of righteousness' and 'trust in the Lord' — complete the night-counsel with its public and private expressions. Right worship and genuine trust are the twin signs that the inner work of verses 4 has been done. The verbal root *batach* (trust) here seeds the nominal *betach* (safety) in verse 8 — a deliberate lexical loop that ties the psalm's imperative to its promise. John Owen's observation about the relationship between mortification and trust is directly applicable: the soul that has quieted itself before God and expressed trust is the soul equipped to sleep (*Mortification of Sin*, ch. 6).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ragaz* → LXX *orgizesthe* → Paul's Ephesians 4:26 — the psalm's own syntax enabled a New Testament reading that made verse 4 universally normative. *Damam* (be still) — the same root as in Psalm 131:2 ('I have composted and quieted my soul') — a silencing that is the fruit of trust, not mere suppression. *Batach* (trust) and *betach* (security/safety) — same root in 4:5 and 4:8, a word-play that closes the loop."
