        "body": "Verse 6 introduces the foil — 'many are saying: Who will show us any good?' The 'many' (*rav*) are not enemies but the broader community of pragmatic questioners whose horizon of hope is the visible and material. Their question is not unspiritual in form; they are asking for 'good' (*tov*). But the question's grammar reveals their orientation: they are waiting for someone to *show them* good from the outside. They have no access to the inner source David is about to describe.\n\nDavid's response is a petition that cites the Aaronic blessing: 'Lift up the light of Your countenance upon us, O Lord' (cf. Numbers 6:25). The 'light of Your face' (*or paneh*) is not metaphorical decoration — it is the most intimate and comprehensive of covenant blessings, the symbol of God's gracious personal attention turned toward His people. To have God's face shining on you is to have everything; to have it withdrawn (as in Psalm 13:1 — 'How long will You hide Your face from me?') is to be in the darkest condition. David asks for the restoration of this full covenant attention.\n\nVerse 7 reports that this has already been received: 'You have put gladness in my heart.' The past tense is not wishful thinking; it is testimony. And the comparison is the verse's intellectual work: 'more than when their grain and new wine abound.' The 'their' is significant — those same 'many' of verse 6. Their highest moment of joy is the harvest's abundance; David's joy in God's face already exceeds it. Douglas Moo's principle from Pillar commentary applies here by analogy: the new-covenant believer's possession surpasses the old covenant's external provisions as surely as David's inner *simchah* surpasses external harvest joy. The psalm is not ascetic (grain and wine are genuine goods, Deuteronomy 7:13); it is comparative — placing the joy of God's presence in its proper category above all created goods.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Simchah* (gladness/joy) — robust, communal, celebratory delight. *Dagan* (grain) and *tirosh* (new wine) — the two primary markers of covenant agricultural blessing in Deuteronomy and the Prophets (Hosea 2:8-9; Joel 2:19). *Or paneh* — the light of the face; *paneh* (face) is one of the most theologically rich words in the OT, appearing in the Aaronic blessing (Numbers 6:25-26) and in Moses's request in Exodus 33:18."
