        "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's resolution, and it works by exclusion rather than addition. David does not say that now, finally, conditions have improved. He does not say that the adversaries of verse 2 have been silenced, that his honor has been publicly restored, or that grain and wine have arrived. He says only: *ki attah Yehovah lebadad betach toshiveini* — 'for You alone, O Lord, in safety cause me to dwell.' The particle *ki* (for/because) gives the sole reason for the peace; the word *badad* (alone, solely, exclusively) eliminates every competing security.\n\nThe word *shalom* (peace) that governs the settling is the Old Testament's most comprehensive term for well-being — it is not the absence of conflict but the presence of completeness. David lies down *in shalom* not because the external world is shalom but because his relationship with Yahweh is intact. The early church fathers recognized this and appointed Psalm 4 for Compline — the last office of the night before sleep — understanding that it was not describing an extraordinary mystical experience but the normal posture of the covenant believer at the day's end.\n\nThe verb *betach* (safety/security) closes the semantic loop opened in verse 5 (*batach*, trust). The psalm has argued: *trust* in the Lord (4:5) → the Lord makes you *dwell in safety* (4:8). The imperative of the middle becomes the promise of the end. Calvin's comment on this verse remains among the finest in the tradition: 'When the ungodly hear the voice of God, they tremble; but when David's head was lying upon the pillow, he was filled with an undoubting confidence that God was his guardian' (*Commentary on the Psalms*, 1557). The sleep of Psalm 4:8 is not the sleep of escape but the sleep of trust — the conscious, volitional rest of a person who has placed the night's circumstances and the day's accusations in the hands of the God who hears when the *chasid* calls.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Badad* (alone/solely) — emphasizes exclusivity; God's protection admits no co-guardian. *Betach* (safety/security) — shares a root with *batach* (trust, 4:5), closing the psalm's own argument. *Shalom* — from a root meaning completeness, wholeness, integrity of relationship."
